The paper evaluates the design decisions made in state-of-the-art constraint solvers, which involves algorithms and data structures used in solving constraint satisfaction problems. This makes it likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses memory management and behaviour with increasing problem size, which are relevant to Programming Languages (cs.PL) and Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-categories. Finally, the paper also briefly considers other design decisions, which could be relevant to Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category.
